---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="CPF and Tax Glossary - Singapore Payroll Terms | SalaryCalculator.sg" description="A comprehensive glossary of Singapore CPF and income tax terms including OW Ceiling, Medisave, IRAS, Employment Pass, and more.">
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "BreadcrumbList",
    "itemListElement": [
      { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "name": "Home", "item": "https://salarycalculator.sg/" },
      { "@type": "ListItem", "position": 2, "name": "Glossary", "item": "https://salarycalculator.sg/glossary/" }
    ]
  })} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
    <nav class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-6">
      <a href="/" class="hover:text-primary">Home</a>
      <span class="mx-2">/</span>
      <span class="text-gray-800">Glossary</span>
    </nav>

    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Singapore CPF and Income Tax Glossary</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-8">A guide to the key terms related to CPF contributions, income tax, and payroll in Singapore. Understanding these concepts will help you interpret your payslip and plan your finances. Terms are listed in alphabetical order.</p>

    <dl class="space-y-6">
      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">AW Ceiling (Additional Wage Ceiling)</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">The Additional Wage (AW) Ceiling limits the amount of additional wages (such as bonuses and Annual Wage Supplement) on which CPF contributions are payable. It is calculated as the difference between the Annual Ordinary Wage Ceiling and the total ordinary wages for the year. This ensures that CPF contributions on combined ordinary and additional wages do not exceed the annual limit.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Bonus/AWS (Annual Wage Supplement)</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">The Annual Wage Supplement, commonly known as the 13th month payment, is a single annual payment that supplements the total amount of wages earned by an employee during the year. AWS is not mandatory under Singapore law but is a common practice. For CPF purposes, AWS is treated as additional wages and is subject to the AW Ceiling.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">CPF (Central Provident Fund)</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">The Central Provident Fund is Singapore's mandatory social security savings scheme. Both employees and employers make monthly contributions based on the employee's wages. The funds are allocated across three accounts (OA, SA, MA) and can be used for housing, retirement, healthcare, and education. CPF applies to Singapore Citizens and Permanent Residents but not to foreigners on work passes.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">CPF Relief</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">CPF Relief is a tax deduction for mandatory CPF contributions made by employees. The employee's share of CPF contributions is automatically granted as a tax relief when filing income tax with IRAS. This means your taxable income is reduced by the amount of CPF you contribute, lowering your overall income tax liability. Voluntary top-ups to your CPF accounts may also qualify for additional tax relief.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Earned Income Relief</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">Earned Income Relief is an automatic tax deduction granted to individuals who have earned income from employment or trade. The relief amount varies by age: a lower amount for those below 55, a higher amount for those aged 55 to 59, and the highest amount for those aged 60 and above. This relief is subject to a cap and is designed to provide greater tax savings for older workers.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Employment Pass (EP)</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">The Employment Pass is a work visa for foreign professionals, managers, and executives who earn above a specified minimum monthly salary. EP holders are not required to contribute to CPF. However, they are still subject to Singapore income tax and must file annual tax returns with IRAS. EP holders are taxed as residents if they have worked in Singapore for at least 183 days in a calendar year.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">IRAS (Inland Revenue Authority of Singapore)</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">IRAS is the statutory board responsible for administering and collecting taxes in Singapore, including income tax, goods and services tax (GST), property tax, and stamp duty. Employees interact with IRAS primarily through the annual income tax filing process, which typically occurs between March and April each year. IRAS also publishes the progressive tax rate tables used by our calculator.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Medisave Account (MA)</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">The Medisave Account is one of the three CPF accounts. It is designed to help members save for healthcare expenses, including hospitalization, approved outpatient treatments, and MediShield Life premiums. The allocation to Medisave increases as a member ages, reflecting higher healthcare needs in later years. There is a Basic Healthcare Sum that caps the amount in the Medisave Account.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Ordinary Account (OA)</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">The Ordinary Account is the most flexible of the three CPF accounts. Funds in the OA can be used for housing purchases (including HDB flats and approved private properties), CPF investment schemes, insurance, and education. The OA receives the largest share of CPF contributions for younger members, with the allocation gradually shifting toward the SA and MA as members age.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">OW Ceiling (Ordinary Wage Ceiling)</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">The Ordinary Wage (OW) Ceiling is the maximum monthly salary on which CPF contributions are calculated. Any ordinary wages earned above this ceiling are not subject to CPF contributions. The OW Ceiling is currently set at $6,800 per month. This means that for employees earning above this amount, CPF contributions are capped based on the ceiling rather than their actual salary.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Personal Relief</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">Personal reliefs are deductions from your assessable income that reduce the amount of income subject to tax. Singapore offers various personal reliefs including Earned Income Relief, CPF Relief, Spouse Relief, Qualifying Child Relief, Parent Relief, and more. The total amount of personal reliefs is capped at $80,000 per Year of Assessment. Each relief has specific qualifying conditions that must be met.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Progressive Tax</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">Singapore uses a progressive income tax system where higher portions of income are taxed at higher rates. Tax rates start at 0% for the first $20,000 of chargeable income and increase in steps up to 24% for income exceeding $1,000,000. This means that only the income within each bracket is taxed at that bracket's rate, not your entire income. The progressive structure ensures that higher earners pay a larger percentage of their income in tax.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">S Pass</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">The S Pass is a work visa for mid-level skilled foreign workers who meet the minimum salary requirement and have relevant qualifications and work experience. Like Employment Pass holders, S Pass holders are not required to contribute to CPF. Employers of S Pass holders must pay a monthly foreign worker levy. S Pass holders are subject to Singapore income tax based on their residency status.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Special Account (SA)</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">The Special Account is a CPF account primarily set aside for retirement savings. Funds in the SA earn a higher interest rate than the Ordinary Account and can be used for retirement-related investments and CPF LIFE annuity premiums. At age 55, the SA is closed and the savings are transferred to the Retirement Account (RA). The SA serves as a long-term savings vehicle that helps ensure adequate retirement income.</dd>
      </div>

      <div>
        <dt class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">Tax Resident</dt>
        <dd class="text-gray-700 mt-1 leading-relaxed">A tax resident in Singapore is an individual who has been physically present or employed in the country for 183 days or more in a calendar year, or who resides in Singapore on a permanent basis. Tax residents are taxed on a progressive rate scale from 0% to 24% and can claim personal reliefs. Non-residents are taxed at a flat rate of 22% (or the progressive rate, whichever is higher) and cannot claim most personal reliefs.</dd>
      </div>
    </dl>
  </div>
</Layout>
